==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*gelwa-'', from Indo-European ''*ghel-, *ghelə-'' ‘shine, glisten’.  Germanic cognates include Old Saxon [[gelo]] (Dutch [[geel]]), Old High German [[gelo]] (German [[gelb]]), Old Norse [[gulr]] (Swedish [[gul]]).  The IE root is also the source of Avestan ''zaray-'' ‘gilded’, Greek [[χλωρος|χλωρός]] ‘pale green’, Latin [[helvus]] ‘honey-yellow’, Old Irish [[gel]] ‘bright white’, Lithuanian [[želvas]] ‘greenish, golden’, Old Church Slavonic [[зеленъ]] (Russian [[зелёный]] ‘green’).

